Forcasting Trends of Women Employed in the Service Providing: Computer and Software (NAIC Code 42343) Sector

Cameron Jester

May 5th, 2023

Image Courtesy of stackadapt.com

Introduction

Hi all!

For this project, I will be looking at changes over time for women employed in the Computer and Software Service sector (NAIC Code 42343). I collected the data from the United States Bureau of Labor Statistics Current Employment Statistics, B-5b. Employment of women by industry sector, not seasonally adjusted and the raw data can be found here!. The available employment data was collected monthly from January 2012 to January 2022 and was given as total employment (in thousands) for both men and women. I compiled the data for both men and women and then calculated percentages for both groups. With this data, I will conduct a time series analysis using methods I learned in my STATS391 course, which includes Decomposition, Autocorrelation, Modeling, Forecasting, etc.

For the second part of my project I will be creating a time series regression model to see the impact of the number of computer science degrees awarded to women on the number of women working in NAIC Code 42343. The regression analysis will follow standard model fitting and residual checking process. The data used for regression was found on the and the raw data from the National Center for Education Statistics can be found here! The data from the NCES collected degree data on a year basis from 2011 to 2020 for men and women. Similar to the working data, I calculated the percentages of degrees awarded for men and women to use for my analysis.

As a young women who will be getting a degree closely related to computer science soon, I am curious to see any potential trends that can be found in this specific cs professional sector.

A few comments to mention before conducting this analysis:

  • The data collected has been separated into mens and womens categories, this is in no way meant to dismiss trans women in this industry, it is simply how government agencies have separated the data.

  • It is also understood that is it not required to have gotten a degree (technology related or not) to be able to work in the technology field. For the sake of drawing conclusions I am using data on women who have gotten computer science degrees in the United States.

  • Thirdly, throughout the project I will be using percentages instead of total number for working and degrees to get a better idea of the differences between women and men in this industry.

Exploratory Data Analysis

First, I am importing the datasets I have created from information found on the United States Bureau of Labor Statistics as well as the National Center for Education Statistics.

working_data <- read_csv("~/Desktop/working_data.csv")
degree_data <- read_csv("~/Desktop/Degree_data.csv")
ts_regression <- read_excel("~/Desktop/ts_regression.xlsx")

The steps to time series analysis:

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis
  2. Decomposing
  3. Stationarity Check
  4. Model Fitting
  5. Diagnostic Checks
  6. Forecasting
  7. Conclusion

Creating TS class

men_pct_ts =ts((working_data[,6]), start = c(2012,1), end = c(2022,12), frequency = 12)
wmn_pct_ts = ts((working_data[,5]), start = c(2012,1), end = c(2022,12), frequency = 12)

Lets look into the monthly data for women holding positions in technology. The following is a sample of the data collected from the USBLS.

head(working_data)

boxplot(wmn_pct_ts~cycle(wmn_pct_ts),main="Monthly Employment Percentages From 2012-2022", xlab = "Month", ylab = "Percentage")

We can see from the boxplot above that the mean stays consistent throughout the year. We do see outliers from the months March to August as well as a smaller range for these months.

The following graph shows the monthly percentage of women working in technology (NAICS code : 42343) from January 2012 to January 2022.

plot(wmn_pct_ts,main="Employment Percentages of Women Working in NAIC Code 42343", sub="From 2012-2022", xlab = "Year", ylab = "Percentage")

From the graph above, we can see some interesting peaks and troughs in this data set. In 2017, there is a sharp drop from 30% to roughly 27%. From 2017 we see an upward trend in the data until a peak is hit in late 2019 of roughly 33.5%. From the model, there are changes in the variance overtime and a very slight seasonal pattern.

Decomposing

As we have monthly data for the women working in technology dataset, it would be worthwhile to decompose the model to look for seasonal trends.

wmnpct_decomp = decompose(wmn_pct_ts)

plot(wmnpct_decomp)

We can see from the trend component of the decomposed plot that the mean is changing over time, which points to non-stationary. Additionally, there does not seem to be a dramatic seasonal component from the decomposed plot. The random noise component of the decomposed plot seems to mirror a similar pattern of troughs in the data in 2017 and 2022, meaning the drops observed will likely not impact the time series analysis.It would be helpful here to conduct an ADF Test to obtain a p-value for our model. The p-value will help us to confirm if this data is indeed non-stationary.

adf.test(wmn_pct_ts)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  wmn_pct_ts
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.2999, Lag order = 5, p-value = 0.4518
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

The p-value here is 0.4518, which means we fail to reject the null at the Alpha Significance Level of 5%. With the ADF Test and the visuals from the original and decomposed plot, it is safe to say the time series model is non-stationary.

Differencing and Log Transformations

To help solve the issue of non-stationarity, I will difference the model. Differencing finds the difference of consecutive observations in the data to eliminate trend.

wmn_pct_diff = diff(wmn_pct_ts)

plot(wmn_pct_diff,main="Differenced Employment Percentages", xlab = "Year", ylab = "Autocorrelation")

By plotting this differenced model, we can see that the mean is now steady across time, meaning a first-order difference was all that was needed to make this data stationary. The variance is not showing an issue here, meaning it does not greatly change over time, therefore it would not be beneficial to continue to the log transformation steps to change the stationarity of this model. To confirm stationarity it would be a good idea to check the ADF and ACF Tests.

adf.test(wmn_pct_diff)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  wmn_pct_diff
## Dickey-Fuller = -3.2049, Lag order = 5, p-value = 0.09018
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

The ADF Test here still gives us a p-value above the Alpha Significance Level of .05, which would mean we fail to reject the null and that the data is non-stationary. One thing to note is that the p-value did decrease roughly .3 after creating a differenced model. It would be best to conduct an ACF Test as well to confirm stationarity.

acf(wmn_pct_diff)

The Autocorrelation Function Plot above highly indicates stationarity as our values stay within the designated 95% Confidence Interval of -.2 and .2.

Based on the differenced plot, the Augmented-Dickey Fuller Test and the AutoCorrelation Function plot, we can confirm that this data is now stationary and we can move onto the model-fitting stage of the analysis.

Model Fitting

To select a model for this data, we must look at the PACF as well as the ACF above.

pacf(wmn_pct_diff)

The ACF and PACF models are indicating that the data is White Noise, meaning that we will not need to fit an AR(p), MA(q), or ARMA(p,q) models. Although, there is a slight lag around time 5 in the ACF plot, so I am going to try to fit an AR(5) model, run diagnostic tests, and see what we get.

AR(5) Model

ar5model = arima(wmn_pct_ts, order = c(5,1,0), include.mean=F)
ar5model

The parameter estimates for the AR(5) model are as follows:

Thi estimation (0.2153)

Standard Error Estimation (0.0862)

Variance Estimation (0.07311)

In addition to the AR(5), I will test an AR(4) and an AR(6) as well to be sure that an AR(5) is the best model for the data

To find the best model for our data, we use the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC), which tells us how well the model fits the data without over-fitting.

The AIC for each model are as follows:

AR(4) AIC : 45.45 AR(5) AIC : 41.39 AR(6) AIC : 43.39

The AR(5) model has the lowest AIC (need to do the AICC as well) of the three test models. In addition to the AICs, the ACF and PACF indicated an AR(5) as well, therefore I will test the diagnostics for this model.

Diagnostic Checks

plot(ar5model$residuals,main="AR(5) Model Residuals", xlab = "Year", ylab = "Residuals")

The plot above seems to be predominantly white noise. Although, there seem to be two sharp drops, one in early 2017 and one in early 2022, this follows the same EDA pattern found in the first plot of the data.

Plotting ACF and PACF

acf(ar5model$residuals)

pacf(ar5model$residuals)

The ACF and PACF also show white noise as all of the lag points are staying within the boundaries of the 95% confidence interval.

Shaprio-Wilks and Ljung Box

Shapiro-Wilks Hypothesis

Ho - The data comes from a normally distributed population

Ha - The data doesnt come from a normally distributed population

Ljung-Box Hypothesis

Ho - The data are independently distributed

Ha - The data are not independently distributed

shapiro.test(ar5model$residuals)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  ar5model$residuals
## W = 0.98881, p-value = 0.3638
Box.test(ar5model$residuals, lag = 20, type = "Ljung-Box")
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  ar5model$residuals
## X-squared = 13.706, df = 20, p-value = 0.8451

With the results from the Shapiro-Wilks test, we fail to reject the null hypothesis, therefore the data suggest it comes from a normally distributed population.

With the results from the Ljung-Box test, we fail to reject the null hypothesis, therefore the data suggests it comes from an independently distributed population and we do not have evidence of serial correlation.

Check normality of residuals

hist(ar5model$residuals)

The histogram above shows a slight left-skew, but is unimodal and seems to follow a normal distribution pretty closely.

Overall, all of the diagnostic checks support the conditions for the AR(5) being a good fit for the data. Therefore, we are confident that the AR(5) is a good model for this data and can be used to obtain forecasted values.

Forecasting

For my forecasted model, I have chosen to forecast the next 12 months of data which will project until December of 2023.

forecast_model = forecast(ar5model, h =12)
table = data.frame(forecast_model)
plot(forecast_model)

As seen from the output above, the forecasted values for women working in the Computer and Software (NAIC Code 42343) sector has a very very small range, which decrease slighly over 12 months. Of all 12 forecasted values, none deviate greater than .18 points away from 30% of employment.

Conclusion

After conducting the time series analysis on the US Bureau of Labor Statistics data, I can conclude that time is not a significant indicator of percentage of employment for women in the Computer and Software Service Providing Sector. I believe that if I had data that went farther back, say 30 or 40 years, I would have likely seen more signal and could have made a different conclusion relating time to job percentages.

Despite time not being a factor for this data, I would like to look into how the number of computer science Bachelors Degrees awarded to women impacts the number of jobs women hold within NAIC code 4243. As the explanatory variable is no longer time, I will have to conduct a time series regression analysis.

Time Series Regression

The steps to time series regression:

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis*
  2. Model Fitting
  3. Residual Checks
  4. Conclusion

*Boxplots and Decomposition are not applicable for this data as it is yearly, and therefore has a frequency of 1.

plot(bac_wmn_pct,main="Percentage of CS Bacehlor's Degrees Awarded to Women", sub = "From 2011-2020", xlab = "Year", ylab = "Percentage")

There is a clear upward trend in the percentage of Computer Science Bachelors degrees awarded to women. Lets see what the trend looks like compared to the percentage of women working to see if any patterns can be visually observed.

ts.plot(cbind(bac_pct, working_pct), gpars = list(col=c("red", "blue"),main = "Employment and CS Degrees Awarded from 2012 - 2021" ,xlab = "Year", ylab= "Percentage"))
legend("left", legend = c("Employment", "Degrees"), col=c("blue", "red"), lty=1)

After plotting both the percentage of computer science degrees awarded to women as well as the employment percentage for women in NAIC code 42343, we can see that there seems to be a slight upward trend in both around early 2017. Neither line shows dramatic variance or trend. After observing the data together, we can move onto fitting a regression model.

Model Fit and Residual Checks

reg_fit = lm(working_percent ~ bac_percent, data = ts_regression)
coef(reg_fit)
## (Intercept) bac_percent 
##   18.639393    0.644805
summary(reg_fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = working_percent ~ bac_percent, data = ts_regression)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -1.70725 -0.40928  0.03399  0.35282  1.47451 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)   
## (Intercept)  18.6394     4.3286   4.306  0.00259 **
## bac_percent   0.6448     0.2281   2.827  0.02224 * 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.8916 on 8 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.4998, Adjusted R-squared:  0.4373 
## F-statistic: 7.994 on 1 and 8 DF,  p-value: 0.02224

From the regression model created, the output gives a p-value of 0.02224 which is a statistically significant at the Alpha Significance Level of 0.05. The data suggests that there is a relationship between percentage of degrees and percentages of workers. Additionally, the Adjusted R-Squared value is 0.437, meaning roughly 44% of the variability in percentage of workers can be associated with its relationship with CS degrees awarded.

The coefficients for the model can be interpreted as:

Intercept: With percentage of degrees awarded held to 0, the percentage of women working in the Computer and Software service providing sector would be at 18.639

Slope: For every 1% increase in the percentage of CS degrees awarded to women, we can predicted that there will be a 0.644 of percentage point increase in the percentage of women working in the Computer and Software service providing sector

checkresiduals(reg_fit)

## 
##  Breusch-Godfrey test for serial correlation of order up to 5
## 
## data:  Residuals
## LM test = 8.6815, df = 5, p-value = 0.1225

Breusch-Godfrey Test Interpretation

H0: There is no autocorrelation at any order less than or equal to p

HA: There exists autocorrelation at some order less than or equal to p

From the Breusch-Godfrey test, our regression residuals yield a p-value of 0.1225. Therefore we fail to reject the null hypothesis and the data suggests that there is no autocorrelation at any order less than or equal to 5.

Histogram Interpretation

The histogram of the residuals shows a slight skew. Despite this, it seems to follow a normal distribution.

ACF Interpretation

The ACF plot shows that at lag 2 the autocorrelation passes the 95% confidence interval, but this value still stays within the designated 5% that we can expect to see outside the interval.

Residual Plot Against Predictors

residual_table = get_regression_points(reg_fit)
gf_point(residual ~ working_percent_hat, data = residual_table, main = "Residuals Against Predicted Values")

From the graph above I see a slight megaphone shape, this might come from the small number of observations in the dataset. From the graph we can also see that there are no X no Y outliers.

Overall, the residual checks for this regression model all seem to pass, with the caveat of having a dataset with less observations than are ideal.

Overall Conclusion

To look at potential predictor variables, I took data from the National Center for Education Statistics for the number of Computer Science degrees awarded to women from 2012 - 2021. After looking at the number of Bachelors degree in CS granted to women, we can see an upward trend, yet the recent increase does not yield as fast of an increase. As we saw from the regression model, for every 1% increase of degrees there is an associated predicted increase of 0.644 of a percentage point increase of employment. While there is a statistically significant relationship, we must remember take into account the limited amount of data. As mentioned in the beginning of this project, a Bachelors degree in computer science is not needed for many entry level position in the Computer and Software sector.

Overall, it can be concluded that time is not an indicator variable for the percentage of women working in NAIC code 42343 but the percentage of CS degrees awarded to women has a slight positive relationship with percentage of women working. I predict if more data was available from 30-40 years ago, as opposed to the last 10 years, time might have had more of an impact on working percentages. In the future I would be interested in looking at other predictor variables that may have an impact on women working in the CS field, as well as revisiting this analysis in the far future when more data is available through the USBLS.
